@HappyFace6or7Yes, of course the off site battery option won't be as efficient as on site. But if the site of the battery is relatively close to the source of the power (within the same city or town) then losses are not going to be as significant.

Many countries already have pumped hydroelectric storage as an offsite option. Obviously the Netherlands is not going to be able to to do that, but a heat storage system is going to be just one option.

Now my house does have room for a battery and I'm OK with that as an option. But the option of grid storage would mean that people who are not so fortunate could at least play a part in solar even now that we are beyond the grid capacity.

@BB-sm8ey Nice to have some metrics ! What about the minimum "temp for some times " needed in some case (like with sodium acetate heat pack system) ? About the surface, I was thinking it could be interesting to use the south side roof of the house, and the storage could be in the back, in an unused side of the house .
Using the roof, or simply collecting the dry and hot air heating under the roof and going out by the upper vent. There, it would dry kind of linked pillows/conveyor belt full of zeolite. When dried enough, the conveyor would run enough time to expose the next "pillow" to the driying place, etc. They'd go to the north's storage, and be used later when needed.
A more basic way could be a solar hoven with a standard meshed box full of zeolite, that we could take off by hand in a waterproof storage when reloaded, then take back into the woodstove, and let drip water on it to release heat when needed.
